    "body": "Hello.[non-fungible-nelson](https://github.com/non-fungible-nelson)  Previously, I encountered an issue where transactions would remain pending in the pool due to the max pool capacity being set to around 4095 by default. When I added \"tx-pool-limit-by-account-percentage=1\" to the configuration, the issue became more evident. I initially raised this concern, but later removed the \"tx-pool-limit-by-account-percentage\" setting because it wasn't supported in the older version. At that time, I was puzzled as to why the transactions weren't getting stuck in the mempool. Now, it's clear that version 23.4.4 has significant flaws.\r\n\r\nMoreover, the stuck 4095 transactions will only clear after 13 hours, given the default setting for --tx-pool-retention-hours is 13 hours, after which they get removed. If you need a visual demonstration, I can provide a video recording. My setup involves two AWS virtual machines, and I run them in command mode without any containers.\r\n\r\nTo summarize, if I don't add pool-limit-by-account-percentage=1, the maximum transaction throughput I achieve is 37 tx per second. Any additional transactions receive a nonce error. However, when I include pool-limit-by-account-percentage=1, the entire system malfunctions, causing transactions to become stuck in the pool for 13 hours, after which they are automatically removed due to the --tx-pool-retention-hours setting.\r\n\r\n![image](https://github.com/hyperledger/besu/assets/13316230/ba0de145-a409-40d3-9f63-e1e3f5d8a0c2)\r\n",
